SIMPLE: idiom
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Idiom
<hw>Id"i*om</hw> <pr>(⟦icr⟧d"⟦icr⟧*⟦ucr⟧m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>idiome</ets>, L. <ets>idioma</ets>, fr. Gr. <grk>'idi`wma</grk>,
fr. <grk>'idioy^n</grk> to make a person's own, to make proper or
peculiar; fr. <grk>'i`dios</grk> one's own, proper, peculiar; prob. akin
to the reflexive pronoun <grk>o"y^</grk>, <grk>o'i^</grk>,
<grk>'e`</grk>, and to <grk>"eo`s</grk>, <grk>'o`s</grk>, one's own, L.
<ets>suus</ets>, and to E. <ets>so</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
syntactical or structural form peculiar to any language; the genius or
cast of a language.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Idiom</qex> may be employed loosely and figuratively as a
synonym of language or dialect, but in its proper sense it signifies the
totality of the general rules of construction which characterize the
syntax of a particular language and distinguish it from other
tongues.</q> <rj><qau>G. P. Marsh.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By <qex>idiom</qex> is meant the use of words which is peculiar to
a particular language.</q> <rj><qau>J. H. Newman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He followed their language [the Latin], but did not comply with
the <qex>idiom</qex> of ours.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An expression conforming or appropriate to the
peculiar structural form of a language.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some that with care true eloquence shall teach,⟦br⟧
And to just <qex>idioms</qex> fix our doubtful speech.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A combination of words having a meaning peculiar to
itself and not predictable as a combination of the meanings of the
individual words, but sanctioned by usage; <as>as, an <ex>idiomatic</ex>
expression</as>; less commonly, a single word used in a peculiar
sense.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is not by means of rules that such <qex>idioms</qex> as the
following are made current: ⟦ldquo⟧I can <examp>make nothing</examp> of
it.⟦rdquo⟧ ⟦ldquo⟧He <examp>treats</examp> his subject
<examp>home</examp>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Dryden</au>. ⟦ldquo⟧It is that within us
that <examp>makes for</examp> righteousness.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>M.
Arnold</au>.</q> <rj><qau>Gostwick (Eng. Gram.)</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sometimes we identify the words with the object -- though by
courtesy of <qex>idiom</qex> rather than in strict propriety of
language.</q> <rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The phrase forms peculiar to a particular author;
<as>as, written in his own <ex>idiom</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Every good writer has much <qex>idiom</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Landor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Dialect; a variant form of a language.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Dialect.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Idiom</er>,
<er>Dialect</er>. The <xex>idioms</xex> of a language belong to its very
structure; its <xex>dialects</xex> are varieties of expression ingrafted
upon it in different localities or by different professions. Each county
of England has some peculiarities of <xex>dialect</xex>, and so have
most of the professions, while the great <xex>idioms</xex> of the
language are everywhere the same. See <er>Language</er>.</usage></p>

<p><ent>Idiomatical</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Idiomatic</ent>⟦br⟧
